"Nielsen L.T., Hallegraeff G.M., Wright S.W., Hansen P.J.","Effects of experimental seawater acidification on an estuarine plankton community",2012,"Aquatic Microbial Ecology","65","3",,"271","285",,,10.3354/ame01554,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-84863880573&partnerID=40&md5=8d92916c498116c76c4762b330e0bc63","Marine Biological Section, University of Copenhagen, Strandpromenaden 5, Helsingør, Denmark; Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies, University of Tasmania, Hobart, TAS, Australia; Australian Antarctic Division, Antarctic Climate and Ecosystems Cooperative Research Centre, Channel Highway, Kingston, TAS, Australia","Nielsen, L.T., Marine Biological Section, University of Copenhagen, Strandpromenaden 5, Helsingør, Denmark; Hallegraeff, G.M., Institute for Marine and Antarctic Studies, University of Tasmania, Hobart, TAS, Australia; Wright, S.W., Australian Antarctic Division, Antarctic Climate and Ecosystems Cooperative Research Centre, Channel Highway, Kingston, TAS, Australia; Hansen, P.J., Marine Biological Section, University of Copenhagen, Strandpromenaden 5, Helsingør, Denmark","The atmospheric CO2 concentration is rising, and models predict that by the end of the century it will have increased to twice the amount seen at any given time during the last 15 million yr. This will cause a decrease in average surface water pH of 0.4, and planktonic protists will be among the organisms to be affected first by this change. We tested whether reduced pH (and increased free CO2) would affect plankton communities over an incubation period of 14 d. In a laboratory microcosm setup using a natural plankton community from the Derwent River estuary, Australia, 2 treatments with reduced pH (8.0 and 7.7) were compared to an unaltered control of pH 8.3. An extreme pH 6.3 was included for comparison. Measured parameters included community photosynthesis, nutrient uptake and biomass build-up as well as enumeration of 25 protist taxa and quantitative HPLC of phytoplankton pigments. A major succession was seen during the 14 d, but no effects at all were found in pH treatments 8.0 and 7.7, whereas the extreme pH 6.3 clearly affected the community for all measured parameters. Thus, it is unlikely that the investigated plankton community would be significantly affected by a pH and CO2 change as predicted for the 21st century. This has previously been found for other coastal plankton assemblages as well, and we suggest that high pH resilience is a necessity for protist species living in coastal waters with relatively large pH fluctuations. © Inter-Research 2012.","Climate change; CO2; pH; Pigment analysis; Plankton; Seawater acidification",,,,,,,"Antoine, D., Andre, J.M., Morel, A., Oceanic primary production. 2. Estimation at global scale from satellite (coastal zone color scanner) chlorophyll (1996) Global Biogeochem Cycles, 10, pp. 57-69; APHA, (2005) Standard Methods for the Examination of Water and Wastewater, 21st Edn, , American Public Health Association, Washington, DC; Beardall, J., Raven, J.A., The potential effects of global climate change on microalgal photosynthesis, growth and ecology (2004) Phycologia, 43, pp. 26-40; Berge, T., Daugbjerg, N., Andersen, B.B., Hansen, P.J., Effect of lowered pH on marine phytoplankton growth rates (2010) Mar Ecol Prog Ser, 416, pp. 79-91; Berges, J.A., Charlebois, D.O., Mauzerall, D.C., Falkowski, P.G., Differential effects of nitrogen limitation on photosynthetic efficiency of photosystems I and II in microalgae (1996) Plant Physiol, 110, pp. 689-696; Boyd, P.W., Doney, S.C., Modelling regional responses by marine pelagic ecosystems to global climate change (2002) Geophys Res Lett, 29; Boyd, P., LaRoche, J., Gall, M., Frew, R., Role of iron, light, and silicate in controlling algal biomass in subantarctic waters SE of New Zealand (1999) J Geophys Res, 104, pp. 13395-13408; Brzezinski, M.A., The Si-C-N ratio of marine diatoms: Interspecific variability and the effect of s